==TeX and LaTeX==
Â and â are obtained by the commands \^A and \^a.

== In encoding mismatches ==
In a common example of mojibake, the capital &quot;Â&quot; is sometimes seen on webpages when the page has been encoded in UTF-8 and decoded using ISO 8859-1 or Windows-1252, two encodings which are commonly referred to as &quot;Western&quot; or &quot;Western European&quot;. In UTF-8, the copyright symbol (©) is encoded with the hexadecimal bytes codice_1. In the older Western encoding standards, however, the © symbol is simply codice_2. If a browser is given the bytes codice_1, intended to display © in UTF-8, but is led to parse the bytes according to one of the Western encodings, it will interpret the bytes codice_1 as two separate characters. codice_5 corresponds to Â, as seen in the chart above, and codice_2 devolves to the © symbol, so the result seen by the person reading the page is codice_7—that is, the correct © symbol but with an Â prepended. Characters with Unicode code points from codice_8 to codice_9 have UTF-8 encodings that are identical to their Western encodings but preceded by the byte codice_5, so that when any of these characters is encoded in UTF-8 and viewed in a Western encoding, an Â will appear before it.

